    • Method Detail

      • nextIdBatch

        IdRange nextIdBatch​(int size,
                    boolean forceConsecutiveAllocation,
                    PageCursorTracer cursorTracer)
        Allocates multiple IDs in one call.
        Parameters:
        size - the number of IDs to allocate.
        forceConsecutiveAllocation - if true the returned IdRange will guarantee that the allocation is a range of IDs where all IDs are consecutive, i.e. an empty IdRange.getDefragIds(). If false there may be some of the allocated IDs non-consecutive, i.e. returned as part of IdRange.getDefragIds().
        cursorTracer - for tracing page accesses.
        Returns:
        an IdRange containing the allocated IDs.

      • maintenance

        void maintenance​(boolean awaitOngoing,
                 PageCursorTracer cursorTracer)
        Does some maintenance. This operation isn't critical for the functionality of an IdGenerator, but may make it perform better. The work happening inside this method should be work that would otherwise happen now and then inside the other methods anyway, but letting a maintenance thread calling it may take some burden off of main request threads.
        Parameters:
        awaitOngoing - awaits any ongoing maintenance operation if another thread does such.
        cursorTracer - underlying page cursor tracer

      • start

        void start​(FreeIds freeIdsForRebuild,
           PageCursorTracer cursorTracer)
    throws IOException
        Starts the id generator, signaling that the database has entered normal operations mode. Updates to this id generator may have come in before this call and those operations must be treated as recovery operations.
        Parameters:
        freeIdsForRebuild - access to stream of ids from the store to use if this id generator needs to be rebuilt when started
        cursorTracer - underlying page cursor tracer
        Throws:
        IOException

      • clearCache

        void clearCache​(PageCursorTracer cursorTracer)
        Clears internal ID caches. This should only be used in specific scenarios where ID states have changed w/o the cache knowing about it.
